Where do I begin? My sister in law made reservations for NYE (which was her birthday). Because of Covid we had 2 different reservations in order to accommodate our party. One was for a party of 6 which was at 5pm and the other for a party of 2 that they made for 4:30. 3 of us arrived at 4:15 so that we could secure our 4:30 reservation.  Upon arrival we explained to them that we had 2 different reservations but wanted to make sure to get there in time for the first one. We were taken back to be seated and was seated at the table for 6 which was the 5pm reservation.  We asked if we could be seated at the table that reserved for 4:30 so that we didn't lose it. After a little back and forth, we were moved to the table that was reserved for 4:30 and told that when the rest of our party arrived at 5, we could adjust and move accordingly.  5pm comes the rest of our party arrives so they sat at the table that was reserved for 5pm.  No big deal right? Wrong! Manager Sean O'Connell comes up to the table and tells them that they can't sit there because they can't just seat themselves.  That would not have been a problem had we not been told by the lady who originally sat us that when our party arrived we could move back to the 5pm table accordingly.  We tried to explain that very calmly to Sean who was not nice at all. The birthday girl asked several times, what did we do wrong? I just want to enjoy my birthday. He just kept saying you need to come up front with me NOW. We all followed him up front still asking, what did we do wrong? We were told we could move to our "previously, already sat at table" when the rest of our party arrived.  Once we got up front, we were asked to leave because we were "causing a scene". Never once did any of us raise our voice,  say anything rude or use any bad language so we are again confused as to what happened. I feel like Sean wanted us to "cause a scene" so that he would feel like he was in the right to ask us to leave. We "being adults who did absolutely nothing wrong as far as we're concerned", asked for his name and left. Unfortunately this completely ruined my sister in laws 55th birthday celebration.  There was a total of 8 of us who had planned on spending good money for dinner. I would say close to if not more than $1000 plus tip. Ruth Chris downtown has lost my business. I usually go for my Birthday often with friends because it falls during Devour.  Not this year. I would tell any and everyone that I know to stay far away from there as possible.  The sad thing is, with all that's going on with downtown and them losing business, you would think they would be a little nicer to their customers and welcome us with open arms and smiling faces.  Not Sean O'Connell! 😔

At first glance everything looks fine. But study the details of the restaurant, and it is ran down! Time for renovations. The booths are all worn out and raggedy. The floor is the same. The walls have spots on them. The booths reminded me of a Denny's meets downtown old strip Vegas vibe. And they turn the lighting down so The worn out isn't as noticeable. Not so much ambience lighting. As for the food, the steaks were amazing. The rest of the food was average. Well, except for the ahi tuna app. That was delicious. The lobster bisque was lukewarm and average at best. The au gratin potatoes were undercooked, and the mashed potatoes were bland bland bland. The Filet Oscar, AMAZING! Absolutely delicious. My husband got the T-bone and it was really good also. They should've warned him that even after the plate was done sizzling that it could still potentially burn your tongue though. They also did this really cute thing at the end because it was our anniversary. And it was adorable and I loved it! I just cannot give it five stars because there were some Misses. I would say it's closer to a 3.5 due to the prices to expensive for everything that was under par. Don't mind paying if it's good. But there was also some great things. More like appetizers entrées and desserts they do wonderful, sides not so much. Also we were told that there was a dress code, and I can assure you that there was not! People were coming in off the streets and we will not discuss or go into detail what they were wearing. But no one was stopping them or saying anything.
